Description: Fix CVE-2026-54371 symlink traversal in getfattr/setfattr
 The getfattr utility (with -R recursive and -h no-dereference) and
 the setfattr --restore utility could be tricked into following
 attacker-controlled symbolic links during pathname resolution,
 allowing local privilege escalation when invoked by a privileged
 process over an attacker-controlled path (CWE-59).
 .
 This backport applies upstream commits 641ea6fc (harden getfattr)
 and 3fb06b9b (harden setfattr --restore) on top of attr 2.4.48.
 Because the upstream fix depends on infrastructure introduced
 between v2.4.48 and 2.6.0 (a new dirfd-based walk_tree, the
 xattrat/openat2 helper family, and the proc-self-fd fallback
 path), those supporting files are vendored as well so the patch
 is self-contained.
 .
 The new infrastructure detects openat2(2) and the *xattrat(2)
 syscalls at configure time. If openat2 is unavailable on the
 target kernel/glibc, the code paths that need it return ENOSYS
 rather than failing to build, preserving compatibility with the
 bullseye toolchain.
 .
 Backport adaptation: the configure.ac and include/Makemodule.am hunks are
 rebased onto the post-quilt Debian 1:2.4.48-6 source tree (after
 debian/patches/series is applied), matching the build environment used
 by the os-patcher fold step.
Origin: upstream, https://git.savannah.nongnu.org/cgit/attr.git/commit/?id=641ea6fcc556c1f34b77efb9cd3f876dff0a0a07
Origin: upstream, https://git.savannah.nongnu.org/cgit/attr.git/commit/?id=3fb06b9ba314d37035d0877e6de313de754f1ac8
Author: Andreas Gruenbacher <agruenba@redhat.com>
Last-Update: 2026-06-30
Bug: https://bugs.debian.org/cgi-bin/bugreport.cgi?bug=1141107

